Package com.opengamma.strata.collect

Class ResultAssert

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.assertj.core.api.AbstractAssert<ResultAssert,​Result<?>>
      • com.opengamma.strata.collect.ResultAssert
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    org.assertj.core.api.Assert<ResultAssert,​Result<?>>, org.assertj.core.api.Descriptable<ResultAssert>, org.assertj.core.api.ExtensionPoints<ResultAssert,​Result<?>>
    public class ResultAssert
extends org.assertj.core.api.AbstractAssert<ResultAssert,​Result<?>>
    An assert helper that provides useful AssertJ assertion methods for Result instances.

    These allow {code Result} instances to be inspected in tests in the same fluent style as other basic classes.

    So the following: 

       Result<SomeType> result = someMethodCall();
   assertTrue(result.isSuccess());
   assertEquals(result.getValue(), SomeType.EXPECTED);
    can be replaced with: 
       Result<SomeType> result = someMethodCall();
   assertThat(result)
     .isSuccess()
     .hasValue(SomeType.EXPECTED);
    The advantage of the latter is that if the result was not a success, the error message produced will detail the failure result. In the former, the only information is that the result was not a success. Note that the isSuccess() call in the latter is unnecessary as it will be checked by the hasValue(Object) method as well.

    In order to be able to use a statically imported assertThat() method for both Result and other types, statically import CollectProjectAssertions.assertThat(Result) rather than this class.
